---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Day Trading Simulator: Practice Strategy & Expectancy",
  description: "Curious if your day trading strategy can actually survive the market? Test your win rate, risk-reward ratio, and expectancy before risking real capital.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-17"
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a day trading simulator?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A day trading simulator is a virtual platform or mathematical tool that allows you to test trading strategies, analyze mathematical expectancy, and practice risk management without putting real money on the line."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do you calculate trading expectancy?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Expectancy is calculated by multiplying your win rate by your average winning trade, and subtracting the product of your loss rate multiplied by your average losing trade. A positive result indicates a profitable system over time."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do most day traders lose money?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Most day traders fail due to a lack of mathematical edge (negative expectancy), poor risk management, over-leveraging positions, and allowing emotions like fear or greed to override their trading plan."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a good win rate for day trading?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A good win rate depends heavily on your risk-reward ratio. Highly profitable trend-following traders may have win rates around 40% but their winning trades are significantly larger than their losers. For strategies with a 1:1 risk-reward, a win rate above 55% is necessary."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does position sizing affect day trading results?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Proper position sizing ensures that no single loss can significantly draw down your account. Even with a profitable expectancy, risking too much per trade can lead to a string of losses that causes a 'risk of ruin', effectively wiping out your capital."
      }
    }
  ]
};

const articleSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": meta.title,
  "description": meta.description,
  "datePublished": meta.published,
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Westmount Fundamentals",
    "url": "https://westmountfundamentals.com"
  }
};

// Combine schemas into an array
const schema = [faqSchema, articleSchema];
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/day-trading-simulator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Day Trading Simulator & Expectancy Calculator</h1>
      <p>Before putting actual capital on the line, it's essential to understand if your trading strategy has a mathematical edge. Use our day trading simulator below to run the numbers, test different win rates, and see how your strategy might perform over a series of trades.</p>



      <div class="calculator-card">
        <h3>Strategy Simulator</h3>
        <p class="text-sm" style="text-align: center; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">Simulate a series of trades to see the mathematical expectancy of your strategy.</p>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="initialCapital">Starting Capital ($)</label>
          <div class="input-wrapper">
            <input type="number" id="initialCapital" min="0" step="100" value="10000">
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="winRate">Win Rate (%)</label>
          <div class="input-wrapper">
            <input type="number" id="winRate" min="0" max="100" step="1" value="50">
            <span class="suffix">%</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="avgWin">Average Winning Trade ($)</label>
          <div class="input-wrapper">
            <span class="suffix" style="right: auto; left: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); pointer-events: none;">$</span>
            <input type="number" id="avgWin" min="0" step="10" value="200" style="padding-left: 2.5rem;">
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="avgLoss">Average Losing Trade ($)</label>
          <div class="input-wrapper">
            <span class="suffix" style="right: auto; left: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); pointer-events: none;">$</span>
            <input type="number" id="avgLoss" min="0" step="10" value="150" style="padding-left: 2.5rem;">
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="numberOfTrades">Number of Trades (Sample Size)</label>
          <div class="input-wrapper">
            <input type="number" id="numberOfTrades" min="1" max="10000" step="1" value="100">
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="calc-result">
          <span class="calc-result-label">Mathematical Expectancy (Per Trade)</span>
          <div class="calc-result-value" id="expectancyResult">$0.00</div>
          <p id="expectancyMessage" style="margin-top: 1rem; font-size: 0.95rem;"></p>
        </div>

        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat-card">
            <span class="calc-result-label">Simulated Final Balance</span>
            <div class="calc-result-value" id="finalBalanceResult" style="font-size: 1.5rem;">$0.00</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-card">
            <span class="calc-result-label">Total Profit/Loss</span>
            <div class="calc-result-value" id="totalProfitResult" style="font-size: 1.5rem;">$0.00</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-card">
            <span class="calc-result-label">Return on Investment</span>
            <div class="calc-result-value" id="roiResult" style="font-size: 1.5rem;">0.00%</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 1.5rem;">
            <button id="runSimBtn" class="btn primary-btn">Run Monte Carlo Simulation</button>
            <p style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-top: 0.5rem;">Click to simulate a random sequence of these trades.</p>
        </div>

      </div>

      <script is:inline>
        document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', () => {
          const initialCapitalInput = document.getElementById('initialCapital');
          const winRateInput = document.getElementById('winRate');
          const avgWinInput = document.getElementById('avgWin');
          const avgLossInput = document.getElementById('avgLoss');
          const numberOfTradesInput = document.getElementById('numberOfTrades');
          const expectancyResult = document.getElementById('expectancyResult');
          const expectancyMessage = document.getElementById('expectancyMessage');
          const finalBalanceResult = document.getElementById('finalBalanceResult');
          const totalProfitResult = document.getElementById('totalProfitResult');
          const roiResult = document.getElementById('roiResult');
          const runSimBtn = document.getElementById('runSimBtn');

          if (!initialCapitalInput) return;

          const formatCurrency = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD' }).format(val);
          const formatPercent = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'percent', minimumFractionDigits: 2 }).format(val / 100);

          function calculateExpectancy() {
            let winRate = parseFloat(winRateInput.value) || 0;
            const avgWin = parseFloat(avgWinInput.value) || 0;
            const avgLoss = parseFloat(avgLossInput.value) || 0;

            if (winRate > 100) winRate = 100;
            if (winRate < 0) winRate = 0;

            const winProb = winRate / 100;
            const lossProb = 1 - winProb;

            const expectancy = (winProb * avgWin) - (lossProb * avgLoss);

            expectancyResult.textContent = formatCurrency(expectancy);

            if (expectancy > 0) {
              expectancyResult.style.color = 'var(--accent-color)';
              expectancyMessage.textContent = "Your strategy has a positive mathematical expectancy. Over a large enough sample size, you are likely to be profitable.";
              expectancyMessage.style.color = 'var(--accent-color)';
            } else if (expectancy < 0) {
              expectancyResult.style.color = 'var(--text-secondary)';
              expectancyMessage.textContent = "Your strategy has a negative mathematical expectancy. The odds are against you, and you are likely to lose money over time.";
              expectancyMessage.style.color = 'var(--text-secondary)';
            } else {
              expectancyResult.style.color = 'var(--text-primary)';
              expectancyMessage.textContent = "Your strategy breaks even. It has zero expectancy.";
              expectancyMessage.style.color = 'var(--text-secondary)';
            }

            return expectancy;
          }

          function runSimulation() {
            const initialCapital = parseFloat(initialCapitalInput.value) || 0;
            let winRate = parseFloat(winRateInput.value) || 0;
            const avgWin = parseFloat(avgWinInput.value) || 0;
            const avgLoss = parseFloat(avgLossInput.value) || 0;
            const numTrades = parseInt(numberOfTradesInput.value) || 0;

            if (winRate > 100) winRate = 100;
            if (winRate < 0) winRate = 0;

            const winProb = winRate / 100;
            let currentBalance = initialCapital;
            let isBust = false;

            for (let i = 0; i < numTrades; i++) {
                if (currentBalance <= 0) {
                    isBust = true;
                    currentBalance = 0;
                    break;
                }

                const randomRoll = Math.random();
                if (randomRoll <= winProb) {
                    // Win
                    currentBalance += avgWin;
                } else {
                    // Loss
                    currentBalance -= avgLoss;
                }
            }

            const totalProfit = currentBalance - initialCapital;
            const roi = initialCapital > 0 ? (totalProfit / initialCapital) * 100 : 0;

            finalBalanceResult.textContent = formatCurrency(currentBalance);
            totalProfitResult.textContent = formatCurrency(totalProfit);
            roiResult.textContent = formatPercent(roi);

            if (isBust) {
                 finalBalanceResult.textContent = "$0.00 (Account Blown)";
                 finalBalanceResult.style.color = 'var(--text-secondary)';
            } else {
                 finalBalanceResult.style.color = 'var(--text-primary)';
            }

            if (totalProfit > 0) {
                totalProfitResult.style.color = 'var(--accent-color)';
                roiResult.style.color = 'var(--accent-color)';
            } else if (totalProfit < 0) {
                totalProfitResult.style.color = 'var(--text-secondary)';
                roiResult.style.color = 'var(--text-secondary)';
            } else {
                totalProfitResult.style.color = 'var(--text-primary)';
                roiResult.style.color = 'var(--text-primary)';
            }
          }

          function updateExpectancyOnly() {
             calculateExpectancy();
          }

          initialCapitalInput.addEventListener('input', updateExpectancyOnly);
          winRateInput.addEventListener('input', updateExpectancyOnly);
          avgWinInput.addEventListener('input', updateExpectancyOnly);
          avgLossInput.addEventListener('input', updateExpectancyOnly);
          numberOfTradesInput.addEventListener('input', updateExpectancyOnly);

          runSimBtn.addEventListener('click', runSimulation);

          // Initial update
          calculateExpectancy();
          runSimulation();
        });
      </script>





      <div class="content-section">
        <h2>What is Day Trading and Why Does It Fail So Often?</h2>
        <p>Day trading involves buying and selling financial instruments within the same trading day to capitalize on short-term price movements. Whether trading stocks, forex, or options, the premise remains the same: close all positions before the market shuts to avoid overnight risk. While it sounds lucrative—and social media often paints it as a quick path to wealth—the reality is starkly different.</p>
        <p>Studies show that over 90% of retail day traders lose money over the long term. But why? Is the market rigged? No. The primary reason for failure is not external manipulation, but rather a lack of understanding of a crucial mathematical concept: <strong>Expectancy</strong>.</p>
        <p>Before ever putting real money on the line, aspiring traders must understand whether their strategy has a mathematical edge. Without an edge, day trading is indistinguishable from gambling at a casino where the house has the advantage. A day trading simulator, like the one provided above, is a critical tool for quantifying that edge.</p>
        <p>If you're looking for more ways to practice, be sure to check out our broader <a href="/trading-simulator">trading simulator</a> and our <a href="/stock-trading-simulator">stock trading simulator</a> to hone your skills.</p>

        <h2>The Mathematics of Trading: Understanding Expectancy</h2>
        <p>At its core, trading is a game of probabilities. You do not need to know what will happen next to make money. You only need to know what will happen <em>over a large sample size of trades</em>. This concept is encapsulated in a single formula known as Trader's Expectancy.</p>

        <h3>The Expectancy Formula</h3>
        <p>Expectancy tells you, on average, how much money you can expect to make (or lose) per trade over a long period. The formula is:</p>
        <div class="highlight-box" style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.2rem; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-weight: bold; color: var(--accent-color);">
          Expectancy = (Win Rate × Average Win) - (Loss Rate × Average Loss)
        </div>

        <p>Let's break down the components:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Win Rate:</strong> The percentage of your trades that are profitable. If you make 100 trades and 40 are winners, your win rate is 40% (or 0.40).</li>
          <li><strong>Loss Rate:</strong> The percentage of your trades that lose money. This is simply 1 minus your win rate. In the example above, the loss rate is 60% (or 0.60).</li>
          <li><strong>Average Win:</strong> The average dollar amount you make on your winning trades.</li>
          <li><strong>Average Loss:</strong> The average dollar amount you lose on your losing trades.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>A Worked Example: The Trend Follower</h3>
        <p>Imagine a trend-following day trader named Alex. Alex uses a breakout strategy that doesn't win very often, but when it does, the profits are substantial. Alex's metrics are:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Win Rate: 35% (0.35)</li>
          <li>Loss Rate: 65% (0.65)</li>
          <li>Average Win: $500</li>
          <li>Average Loss: $150</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Let's plug these numbers into the formula:</p>
        <code>Expectancy = (0.35 × $500) - (0.65 × $150)</code><br>
        <code>Expectancy = ($175) - ($97.50)</code><br>
        <code>Expectancy = $77.50</code>
        <p>This means that, on average, Alex expects to make $77.50 for every single trade executed, <em>even though he loses 65% of the time</em>. Over a sample of 100 trades, Alex can expect a gross profit of $7,750. This is the power of a positive expectancy model. You do not need a high win rate to be highly profitable.</p>

        <h3>A Worked Example: The Scalper</h3>
        <p>Now consider a scalper named Jordan. Jordan likes to take quick, small profits and has a very high win rate. However, when a trade goes against Jordan, the losses tend to be larger because Jordan holds onto losers hoping they will bounce back. Jordan's metrics are:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Win Rate: 80% (0.80)</li>
          <li>Loss Rate: 20% (0.20)</li>
          <li>Average Win: $50</li>
          <li>Average Loss: $300</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Let's calculate Jordan's expectancy:</p>
        <code>Expectancy = (0.80 × $50) - (0.20 × $300)</code><br>
        <code>Expectancy = ($40) - ($60)</code><br>
        <code>Expectancy = -$20.00</code>
        <p>Despite winning 8 trades out of 10, Jordan has a negative expectancy. On average, Jordan loses $20 per trade. Over 100 trades, this strategy will slowly bleed $2,000 from the account. This is why high win rates can be deceptive and why new traders often blow up their accounts despite feeling like they are "mostly right."</p>

        <h2>Real-World Context: When Would an Investor Use This?</h2>
        <p>The expectancy model isn't just a theoretical exercise; it is the foundation of systematic trading and investing. Here is how professionals apply these concepts in the real world:</p>

        <h3>1. Backtesting Strategies</h3>
        <p>Before risking capital, algorithmic and quantitative traders will run historical data through their trading rules—a process known as backtesting. The output of a backtest provides the raw data (win rate, average win, average loss) needed to calculate expectancy. If a backtest yields a negative expectancy, the strategy is discarded or refined. To practice this safely, many traders start with a <a href="/paper-trading-simulator">paper trading simulator</a> to gather forward-tested data without risk.</p>

        <h3>2. Adjusting Risk-Reward Ratios</h3>
        <p>If a trader knows their historical win rate is locked in at around 45%, they can use the expectancy formula to determine exactly what their risk-reward ratio must be to remain profitable. For a 45% win rate, the average win <em>must</em> be significantly larger than the average loss. This mathematical reality forces the trader to ruthlessly cut losers short and let winners run.</p>

        <h3>3. Assessing Strategy Degradation</h3>
        <p>Market conditions change. A strategy that worked well during a bull market might falter during sideways consolidation. Professional traders continuously monitor their rolling 30-day or 50-day expectancy. If the expectancy drops near zero or goes negative, it is a mathematical signal to stop trading that specific system until market conditions align with the strategy again.</p>

        <h2>Common Mistakes People Make With Expectancy</h2>
        <p>Understanding the math is only half the battle. Applying it requires discipline. Here are the most common pitfalls traders encounter:</p>

        <h3>The Law of Small Numbers</h3>
        <p>Expectancy is a long-term mathematical concept. It requires a large sample size to play out accurately. If your strategy has a 60% win rate, it is still entirely mathematically possible to lose five, six, or even ten trades in a row. New traders often abandon a perfectly profitable, positive-expectancy strategy after a short string of losses because they fail to understand the law of small numbers. You must execute a large enough sample (e.g., 50 to 100 trades) for the edge to materialize.</p>

        <h3>Ignoring Commission and Slippage</h3>
        <p>The examples above calculated gross expectancy. However, in the real world, you must account for friction. Commissions (fees paid to the broker) and slippage (the difference between expected price and actual fill price) eat into your average win and add to your average loss. A strategy with a gross expectancy of $5.00 might actually be a negative expectancy strategy once you factor in $3.00 per trade in round-trip commissions and $3.00 in slippage. Always calculate <em>net expectancy</em>.</p>

        <h3>Position Sizing and the Risk of Ruin</h3>
        <p>Having a positive expectancy does not guarantee success if your position sizing is flawed. If you have a highly profitable strategy but you risk 50% of your account on a single trade, you will inevitably hit a normal losing streak and blow up your account (a concept known as the risk of ruin). Professional traders rarely risk more than 1% to 2% of their total capital on a single day trade. Proper position sizing ensures you survive long enough to let the positive expectancy work in your favor.</p>

        <h2>Practical Tips and Rules of Thumb from Professionals</h2>
        <p>If you are serious about treating day trading as a business rather than a casino trip, adhere to these professional rules of thumb:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>The 1% Rule:</strong> Never risk more than 1% of your total account equity on a single trade. If you have a $50,000 account, your maximum loss on any given setup should be strictly capped at $500.</li>
          <li><strong>The 2:1 Minimum:</strong> For most discretionary day traders, aim for setups that offer at least a 2:1 Reward-to-Risk ratio. If you are risking $100 to the downside (your stop loss), your logical profit target should be at least $200. This ensures that even with a modest 40% win rate, you maintain a strong positive expectancy.</li>
          <li><strong>Track Everything:</strong> You cannot calculate your expectancy if you do not track your data. Maintain a meticulous trading journal that logs your entry, exit, position size, and the rationale for the trade. Periodically review your metrics to ensure your edge is intact.</li>
          <li><strong>Trade the System, Not the Outcome:</strong> Once you have verified that your system has a positive mathematical expectancy, your only job is execution. Do not attach emotion to individual trades. An individual trade is just one random data point in a large statistical sample. Accept the losses as the necessary cost of doing business.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Comparing Trading to Long-Term Investing</h2>
        <p>It's important to contrast day trading with long-term investing. Day trading relies on extracting small, frequent profits based on short-term price inefficiencies. It is highly active, stressful, and requires constant screen time.</p>
        <p>In contrast, long-term investing relies on the fundamental growth of companies and the overall economy over decades. By looking at the <a href="/average-stock-market-return">average stock market return</a>, passive investors can achieve significant wealth creation without the need to calculate complex trade expectancies or manage minute-by-minute risk.</p>
        <p>If you are holding positions overnight or over years, corporate actions also come into play. For instance, understanding a <a href="/stock-split-calculator">stock split</a> is relevant for an investor holding a company for years, but entirely irrelevant to a day trader who is only focused on today's price action.</p>

        <p>Ultimately, day trading is not for everyone. It requires immense discipline, statistical understanding, and emotional control. Use the simulator at the top of this page extensively. Run the numbers, face the mathematical realities of your strategy, and never risk capital until you can prove, statistically, that you have an edge.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is a day trading simulator?</h3>
          <p>A day trading simulator is a virtual platform or mathematical tool that allows you to test trading strategies, analyze mathematical expectancy, and practice risk management without putting real money on the line.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How do you calculate trading expectancy?</h3>
          <p>Expectancy is calculated by multiplying your win rate by your average winning trade, and subtracting the product of your loss rate multiplied by your average losing trade. A positive result indicates a profitable system over time.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Why do most day traders lose money?</h3>
          <p>Most day traders fail due to a lack of mathematical edge (negative expectancy), poor risk management, over-leveraging positions, and allowing emotions like fear or greed to override their trading plan.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is a good win rate for day trading?</h3>
          <p>A good win rate depends heavily on your risk-reward ratio. Highly profitable trend-following traders may have win rates around 40% but their winning trades are significantly larger than their losers. For strategies with a 1:1 risk-reward, a win rate above 55% is necessary.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How does position sizing affect day trading results?</h3>
          <p>Proper position sizing ensures that no single loss can significantly draw down your account. Even with a profitable expectancy, risking too much per trade can lead to a string of losses that causes a 'risk of ruin', effectively wiping out your capital.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>


<style>
